Austria
Introduction of a "golden rule" budgetary in the Constitution
The Government of great social democratic/christian democrat coalition that is in the power in Austria has determined Tuesday to include in the Constitution a "golden rule" budgetary to reduce the public deficit and, thus, to avoid a possible degradation of the sovereign note of Austria on the part of the agencies of credit qualification (triple TO).
It was the own social democratic Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Cabinet, when the Austrian public debt reaches the 74,6%, a figure very over the maximum limit of the 60% set by the tried Maastricht, but clearly lower to the debts of countries as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the reliability of Austria in a single level was reduced, of AAA to AA +, we would have that to pay 3,000 million euro more in interests each year", indicated the christian democrat Vice-chancellor of Exterior Matters, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria responds thus to a petition of the Summit from Brussels to the member countries of the zone of the euro of last October 26: in her, the Heads of state and of Government they asked the inclusion, before ends of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and of the recovery of the equilibrium of the public accounts in the Constitution or in a Law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian Government approaches the "model German", since Germany was the first European country that adopted that type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should diminish each year in a 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP) and, from the 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal State should not surpass each year the 0.35% of the GDP, while the regional States, as well as the comunas, they should present stable budgets.
The objective consists of that, toward 2020/2021, the public debt be reduced under the criterion of the 60% set by the tried Maastricht.
