If there is a theme that itself cannot treat keeping in mind considerations of short time limit or simply thinking about the emotions, is the energy policies.
The availability and the price of the electricity influence directly in the purchasing power and in the competitiveness of the businesses.
Turns out to be adequate that an electoral encounter be the moment to reflect on such questions and on the place of the nuclear energy.
The debate only will turn out to be useful if studies the assembly of the environmental, social, and economic consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion in objective facts, in rational data.
Now that we are 7,000 million people in the planet, the demographic evolution will suppose the duplication of the electric demand before 2050, unless be deprived to an enormous part of the world population of a vital element.
At the same time, there will be that to alleviate the shortage each greater time of the resources fossils to continue producing electricity continuously, without forget the imperious need to reduce the emissions of greenhouse gases for fight against the climatic change, a theme that has disappeared of the ecological debate.
The accident of Fukushima modifies none of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce the nuclear energy.
That it is not the case neither of Belgium, that submits his to the need to find a capable source to substitute it, neither of Switzerland, that only considers objective to build head offices of the latest generation.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, Czech Republic, Netherlands, Sweden, south Africa, Chinese, India and Brazil, by citing some examples, they continue ahead with decision with their projects.
The United States, by their side, after Fukushima they decided to add a unit to their park, taking up again the construction of a head office interrupted after the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on the renewable energies, is presented from time to time as an example, the reality goes against such speech.
The election of Berlin is going to suppose an increase of the price of the electricity, a greater energy dependence by the need increased of gas imported, particularly of Russia, an increase of the emissions of CO2 by the gas head offices construction and of coal.
In some months, the damaging effects will be noted.
He should be meditated on the case of Denmark.
Champion of Europe in the Aeolian sector, of which obtains the 30% of their electricity, is also one of the large users of coal and of gas due to the intermittence of the wind; by this reason, its emissions of CO2 and the price of its electricity are, respectively, a 65% and a 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policies, our neighbors credit a bill of electricity a 40% superior to that of the French homes.
While in an economy globalized the price of the energy constitutes a key factor of the competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial utility in the national territory, the French businesses are benefited of the cheapest electricity of Europe.
By that reason, any significant reduction of the nuclear energy would suppose a strong ascent of the price of the electricity, what would reduce realism to the marvelous statements on the restructuring of industry of our country and the defense of ours purchasing power.
It is a matter of a price that the great majority of the French refuse to pay and, in fact, they do not declare opposition by principle to that type of energy, they as show the surveys.
