The only difference is in the degree of generosity with the one that act with regard to the immigrants.
In its program, François Hollande is limited to include banalities, indicating that the codesarrollo will permit to solve the "problem of the migration".
This idea of the immigration as a load, a problem, perhaps turns out to be profitable electorally, but economically leaves very expensive.
Just as they indicate the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent work that summarizes the most recent know-how on the immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Defines Our Future, May of 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), an extensive consensus among the specialists on the positive impact of the migratory flows in the economic growth exists, the salaries and the employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
The limitation of the immigration weakens the growth and damages to the employment.
The fears related to the impact of the immigrants are based on the idea that these they can replace the national workers, particularly to the little qualified, pressuring so that its salaries be reduced.
But the experience shows that, in reality, the immigrants are more well complementary than replacements of the national workers and exercise chiefly professions in sectors with lack of employment.
The immigrants little qualified work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where the formation does not satisfy the demand of personnel.
A positive effect on the salaries
In the same way that a surgeon would have difficulties to work in a country that have lack of anesthetists, the complementariedad between national and immigrants he causes that the arrival of these last he influence positively in the salaries and the employment of the national.
Keeping in mind the previous thing, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of the 1% of the migratory flows supposes an ascent of the long-term real salaries from among a 0.6 and a 0,9%.
And, without keep in mind the fact that the diversity that contribute the immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and to the economic growth (a great proportion of American Nobel prizes exists naturalized and businesses as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
The immigrants are also net taxpayers to the social systems, since they contribute of average a 1% of the total budget in the European countries.
The International Organization of the Work calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant that arrive with an age of 30 years will carry out a net contribution (incomes less expenses) of 150,000 euro to the public budgets of average during all his life.
At the beginning of their mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to be going to seek the points of growth that lacked him "with the teeth".
Said teeth, that dissuaded the immigrants, they had exactly the inverse effect.
